You may resume baths or showers the day after surgery. Do not physically touch/scrub the
surgical area. Let water run over this area and pat dry when finished.
You may resume baths or showers the day after the dressing is removed (see dressing
instructions) or falls off. Do not physically touch/scrub the surgical area. Let water run over
this area and pat dry when finished.
There is a penile dressing around the penis. The dressing will often fall off on its own,
sometimes shortly after surgery. This is expected and normal. If the dressing has not fallen off
by tomorrow (day after surgery), remove it.
There is a stent/catheter exiting the penis. Allow to drain into the … Do not submerge the

You have a ureteral stent. This is a temporary, indwelling device and must be removed.
You have a ureteral stent on a string. This is a temporary, indwelling device and must be
removed. Please pull the stent out by gently pulling on the string in *** days. This is best done
on a weekday in the morning in the shower.

You have a urethral catheter in place. This will drain to … If the catheter comes out earlier
than planned, please call your urology doctor's office immediately.
You have a suprapubic catheter in place. This will drain to … If the catheter comes out earlier

If the catheter dislodges, contact urology doctor's office immediately. Flush the bladder via the
catheter with 30-50 mL of sterile water or normal saline as needed (no more than 3x/day) for
no or decreased urine output, mucous/debris, or blood clots.
Void every 2-3 hours while awake, stay hydrated, and avoid constipation. You may use over
the counter stool softeners or MiraLax as needed for constipation.
Oxycodone can be administered with Tylenol (acetaminophen) when your child is
experiencing severe or breakthrough pain. Oxycodone may make your child drowsy or
constipated. Please hydrate your child and add a stool softer from your local pharmacy if
needed. The DEA and FDA recommend discarding narcotic medications by returning them to
a "take-back location." Children's Hospital of Colorado is an authorized participant in the
Colorado Medication Take Back Program and has a green collection bin located in the lobby
of the hospital for your convenience. Additional take back sites and other methods of disposal
are found at www.takemedsback.org. Prescription narcotics should not be kept in the house
for safety reasons. Alternatively, the FDA recommends the medication can be safely flushed
down the toilet. Do not share this medication.
It is not uncommon after a stone procedure for patient to pass small stone fragments (sand).
Please encourage oral fluids to help pass these fragments.
It is common for patient to experience bladder spasms or flank pain related to catheters,
recent instrumentation, or presence of a ureteral stent. Ditropan (oxybutynin) is used for
bladder spasms as needed. These may be apparent if there is bladder/abdominal pain and/or
urine is leaking in spurts, sometime around the urinary catheter. Please discontinue use of
oxybutynin the day before the catheter is to be removed. Oxybutynin causes constipation and
dry mouth. Encourage plenty of oral fluids and stool softeners as needed while taking this
It is normal to have some blood in the urine and burning with urination after the procedure.
Please encourage oral fluid intake to dilute urine. The blood in the urine may be intermittent
(not present for several days or weeks and then present). This is expected and normal.
Flomax (tamsulosin) is used for flank or bladder pain related to a ureteral stent or kidney
stone in the ureter. It is best taken daily to relax the ureter. If you have a stent, take up to and
including the day the stent is removed. If you have a stone, take it for the specified period of
time. Stop the medication if your child passes the stone or stent is removed.
There is surgical glue over the incision(s). It will flake off on its own over the next 1-2 weeks.
Do not peel off early or apply lotion/ointment to the area.
Scrotal support (jock strap) is in place with fluffs. Leave in place for 2-3 days. Change as
needed. May be removed or used after this as desired.
It is expected for the penis to be red, swollen with bruising for 2-3 weeks. This is normal and
will improve with time. Change diaper per normal routine.
It is expected for the penis to be red, swollen with bruising for 2-3 weeks. This is normal and
will improve with time. Change underwear as needed. May use gauze as barrier layer.
It is normal to see bruising and swelling around the incision(s) for the next few weeks.
